                <head>124. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On September 28 Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                        >McNamara</persName>, who had just returned to Washington from a 2-day
                    inspection trip in West Germany, stated at a press conference that the Berlin
                    situation, in military terms, was the most severe since actual combat operations
                    during the Korean war. <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> then
                    stated that <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName>’s insistence on a
                    peace treaty with East Germany and the consequent restriction of U.S. rights in
                    Berlin made the situation critical. To be sure that there were no illusions in
                    the Soviet Union, <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> noted the
                    United States would “utilize whatever weapons are needed to preserve our vital
                    interests. Quite clearly, we consider access to Berlin a vital interest.” For
                    extracts from the press conference, see The New York Times, September 29,
                    1962.</p>
            </div>
